# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ldap-directory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:ldap-directory/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:ldap-directory/identity-and-access-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) allows an application to remotely perform operations such as searching and modifying records in directories.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] LDAP injection results from inadequate input sanitization and validation and allows malicious users to glean restricted information using the directory service.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] For general information about LDAP please visit lightweight directory access protocol (LDAP).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] LDAP Injection is an attack used to exploit web based applications that construct LDAP statements based on user input.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] When an application fails to properly sanitize user input, it's possible to modify LDAP statements through techniques similar to SQL Injection.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] This cheatsheet is focused on providing clear, simple, actionable guidance for preventing LDAP Injection flaws in your applications.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The widespread use of LDAP to authenticate users to systems.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] LDAP injection attacks could result in the granting of permissions to unauthorized queries, and content modification inside the LDAP tree.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The main way LDAP stores names is based on DN (distinguished name).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] You can think of this like a unique identifier.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] These are sometimes used to access resources, like a username.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] An allowlist can be used to restrict input to a list of valid characters.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Characters and character sequences that must be excluded from allowlists — including Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) metacharacters and LDAP special characters — are listed in the following list.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The exhaustive list is the following: `\ # + < > , ; " =` and leading or trailing spaces.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Each DN points to exactly 1 entry, which can be thought of sort of like a row in a RDBMS.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] For each entry, there will be 1 or more attributes which are analogous to RDBMS columns.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you are interested in searching through LDAP for users with certain attributes, you may do so with search filters.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] In a search filter, you can use standard boolean logic to get a list of users matching an arbitrary constraint.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Search filters are written in Polish notation AKA prefix notation.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] When building LDAP queries in application code, you MUST escape any untrusted data that is added to any LDAP query.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding for LDAP Search and Encoding for LDAP DN (distinguished name).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The proper escaping depends on whether you are sanitizing input for a search filter, or you are using a DN as a username-like credential for accessing some resource.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] For more information on search filter escaping visit RFC4515.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] The following solution uses an allowlist to sanitize user input so that the filter string contains only valid characters.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] In this code, userSN may contain only letters and spaces.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] When a database field must include special characters, it is critical to ensure that the authentic data is stored in sanitized form in the database and also that any user input is normalized before the validation or comparison takes place.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Using characters that have special meanings in JNDI and LDAP in the absence of a comprehensive normalization and allowlisting-based routine is discouraged.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Special characters must be transformed to sanitized, safe values before they are added to the allowlist expression against which input will be validated.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Likewise, normalization of user input should occur before the validation step (source: Prevent LDAP injection).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] For further information visit OWASP ESAPI Java Encoder Project which includes encodeForLDAP(String) and encodeForDN(String).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] .NET AntiXSS (now the Encoder class) has LDAP encoding functions including `Encoder.LdapFilterEncode(string)`, `Encoder.LdapDistinguishedNameEncode(string)` and `Encoder.LdapDistinguishedNameEncode(string, bool, bool)`.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] `Encoder.LdapFilterEncode` encodes input according to RFC4515 where unsafe values are converted to `\XX` where `XX` is the representation of the unsafe character.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] `Encoder.LdapDistinguishedNameEncode` encodes input according to RFC2253 where unsafe characters are converted to `#XX` where `XX` is the representation of the unsafe character and the comma, plus, quote, slash, less than and great than signs are escaped using slash notation (`\X`).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] In addition to this a space or octothorpe (`#`) at the beginning of the input string is `\` escaped as is a space at the end of a string.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] `LdapDistinguishedNameEncode(string, bool, bool)` is also provided so you may turn off the initial or final character escaping rules, for example if you are concatenating the escaped distinguished name fragment into the midst of a complete distinguished name.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] We recommend using LINQ to LDAP (for .NET Framework 4.5 or lower until it has been updated) in DotNet.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] It provides automatic LDAP encoding when building LDAP queries.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Contact the Readme file in the project repository.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Beyond adopting one of the two primary defenses, we also recommend adopting all of these additional defenses in order to provide defense in depth.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] To minimize the potential damage of a successful LDAP injection attack, you should minimize the privileges assigned to the LDAP binding account in your environment.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] If LDAP protocol is configured with bind Authentication, attackers would not be able to perform LDAP injection attacks because of verification and authorization checks that are performed against valid credentials passed by the user.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] An attacker can still bypass bind authentication through an anonymous connection or by exploiting the use of unauthenticated bind: Anonymous Bind (LDAP) and Unauthenticated Bind (LDAP).
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] Input validation can be used to detect unauthorized input before it is passed to the LDAP query.
[src:ldap-directory/ldap-injection-prevention-cheat-sheet] For more information please see the Input Validation Cheat Sheet.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Despite its name, LDAP is much more than its protocol (i.e., much more than its HTTP API); it includes specifications of the required operation of systems satisfying its HTTP API and even specifies a standardized model of the data to be used by the HTTP API and managed by the directory service.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory services play an important role in developing intranet and Internet applications by allowing the sharing of information about users, systems, networks, services, and applications throughout the network.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As examples, directory services may provide any organized set of records, often with a hierarchical structure, such as a corporate email directory.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, a telephone directory is a list of subscribers with an address and a phone number.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common use of LDAP is to provide a central place to store usernames and passwords.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This allows many different applications and services to connect to the LDAP server to validate users.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is a simpler (*lightweight*) subset of the standards in the X.500 series, particularly the X.511 Directory Access Protocol.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Because of this relationship, LDAP is sometimes called **X.500 Lite**.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Telecommunication companies' understanding of directory requirements were well developed after some 70 years of producing and managing telephone directories.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These companies introduced the concept of directory services to information technology and computer networking, their input culminating in the comprehensive X.500 specification, a suite of protocols produced by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the 1980s.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] X.500 directory services were traditionally accessed via the X.511 Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which required the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) protocol stack.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP was originally intended to be a lightweight alternative protocol for accessing X.500 directory services through the simpler (and now widespread) TCP/IP protocol stack.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This model of directory access was borrowed from the DIXIE and Directory Assistance Service protocols.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The protocol was originally created by Tim Howes of the University of Michigan, Steve Kille of Isode Limited, Colin Robbins of Nexor and Wengyik Yeong of Performance Systems International, circa 1993, as a successor to DIXIE and DAS.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Mark Wahl of Critical Angle Inc., Tim Howes, and Steve Kille started work in 1996 on a new version of LDAP, LDAPv3, under the aegis of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPv3, first published in 1997, superseded LDAPv2 and added support for extensibility, integrated the Simple Authentication and Security Layer, and better aligned the protocol to the 1993 edition of X.500.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Further development of the LDAPv3 specifications themselves and of numerous extensions adding features to LDAPv3 has come through the IETF.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the early engineering stages of LDAP, it was known as *Lightweight Directory Browsing Protocol*, or *LDBP*.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was renamed with the expansion of the scope of the protocol beyond directory browsing and searching, to include directory update functions.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was given its *Lightweight* name because it was not as network intensive as its DAP predecessor and thus was more easily implemented over the Internet due to its relatively modest bandwidth usage.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP has influenced subsequent Internet protocols, including later versions of X.500, XML Enabled Directory (XED), Directory Service Markup Language (DSML), Service Provisioning Markup Language (SPML), and the Service Location Protocol (SLP).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It is also used as the basis for Microsoft's Active Directory.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A client starts an LDAP session by connecting to an LDAP server, called a Directory System Agent (DSA), by default on TCP and UDP port 389, or on port 636 for LDAPS (LDAP over TLS/SSL, see below).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client then sends an operation request to the server, and a server sends responses in return.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] With some exceptions, the client does not need to wait for a response before sending the next request, and the server may send the responses in any order.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] All information is transmitted using Basic Encoding Rules (BER).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In addition the server may send "Unsolicited Notifications" that are not responses to any request, e.g. before the connection is timed out.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common alternative method of securing LDAP communication is using an SSL tunnel.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The default port for LDAP over SSL is 636.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The use of LDAP over SSL was common in LDAP Version 2 (LDAPv2) but it was never standardized in any formal specification.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This usage has been deprecated along with LDAPv2, which was officially retired in 2003.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A DN may change over the lifetime of the entry, for instance, when entries are moved within a tree.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To reliably and unambiguously identify entries, a UUID might be provided in the set of the entry's *operational attributes*.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`dn`" is the distinguished name of the entry; it is neither an attribute nor a part of the entry.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`cn=John Doe`" is the entry's RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), and "`dc=example,dc=com`" is the DN of the parent entry, where "`dc`" denotes 'Domain Component'.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The other lines show the attributes in the entry.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attribute names are typically mnemonic strings, like "`cn`" for common name, "`dc`" for domain component, "`mail`" for email address, and "`sn`" for surname.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A server holds a subtree starting from a specific entry, e.g.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may also hold references to other servers, so an attempt to access "`ou=department,dc=example,dc=com`" could return a *referral* or *continuation reference* to a server that holds that part of the directory tree.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client can then contact the other server.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some servers also support *chaining*, which means the server contacts the other server and returns the results to the client.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP rarely defines any ordering: The server may return the values of an attribute, the attributes in an entry, and the entries found by a search operation in any order.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This follows from the formal definitions - an entry is defined as a set of attributes, and an attribute is a set of values, and sets need not be ordered.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The ADD operation inserts a new entry into the directory-server database.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the distinguished name in the add request already exists in the directory, then the server will not add a duplicate entry but will set the result code in the add result to decimal 68, "entryAlreadyExists".
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the above example, `uid=user,ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must not exist, and `ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must exist.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When an LDAP session is created, that is, when an LDAP client connects to the server, the **authentication state** of the session is set to anonymous.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The BIND operation establishes the authentication state for a session.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Simple BIND and SASL PLAIN can send the user's DN and password in plaintext, so the connections utilizing either Simple or SASL PLAIN should be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server typically checks the password against the `userPassword` attribute in the named entry.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Anonymous BIND (with empty DN and password) resets the connection to anonymous state.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] SASL (Simple Authentication and Security Layer) BIND provides authentication services through a wide range of mechanisms, e.g.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Kerberos or the client certificate sent with TLS.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND also sets the LDAP protocol version by sending a version number as an integer.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the client requests a version that the server does not support, the server must set the result code in the BIND response to the code for a protocol error.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Normally clients should use LDAPv3, which is the default in the protocol but not always in LDAP libraries.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND had to be the first operation in a session in LDAPv2, but is not required as of LDAPv3.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In LDAPv3, each successful BIND request changes the authentication state of the session and each unsuccessful BIND request resets the authentication state of the session.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an entry, an LDAP client transmits a properly formed delete request to the server.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Search operation is used to both search for and read entries.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name of the base object entry (or possibly the root) relative to which the search is to be performed.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] What elements below the baseObject to search.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] (the entire subtree starting at the base DN).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Criteria to use in selecting elements within scope.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] determine whether the values for those attributes match the filter assertion.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Note that a common misconception is that LDAP data is case-sensitive, whereas in fact matching rules and ordering rules determine matching, comparisons, and relative value relationships.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Which attributes to return in result entries.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Maximum number of entries to return, and maximum time to allow search to run.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These values, however, cannot override any restrictions the server places on size limit and time limit.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Return attribute types only, not attribute values.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server returns the matching entries and potentially continuation references.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The final result will include the result code.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Compare operation takes a DN, an attribute name and an attribute value, and checks if the named entry contains that attribute with that value.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation is used by LDAP clients to request that the LDAP server make changes to existing entries.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attempts to modify entries that do not exist will fail.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] MODIFY requests are subject to access controls as implemented by the server.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation requires that the distinguished name (DN) of the entry be specified, and a sequence of changes.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To replace the value of an existing attribute, use the `replace` keyword.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to update.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an attribute from an entry, use the keyword `delete` and the changetype designator `modify`.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to delete.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is also a Modify-Increment extension which allows an incrementable attribute value to be incremented by a specified amount.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When LDAP servers are in a replicated topology, LDAP clients should consider using the post-read control to verify updates instead of a search after an update.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The post-read control is designed so that applications need not issue a search request after an update – it is bad form to retrieve an entry for the sole purpose of checking that an update worked because of the replication eventual consistency model.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP client should not assume that it connects to the same directory server for each request because architects may have placed load-balancers or LDAP proxies or both between LDAP clients and servers.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Modify DN (move/rename entry) takes the new RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), optionally the new parent's DN, and a flag that indicates whether to delete the value(s) in the entry that match the old RDN.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may support renaming of entire directory subtrees.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An update operation is atomic: Other operations will see either the new entry or the old one.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] On the other hand, LDAP does not define transactions of multiple operations: If you read an entry and then modify it, another client may have updated the entry in the meantime.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may implement extensions that support this, though.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Extended Operation is a generic LDAP operation that can define new operations that were not part of the original protocol specification.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] StartTLS is one of the most significant extensions.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Other examples include Cancel and Password Modify.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The StartTLS operation establishes Transport Layer Security (the descendant of SSL) on the connection.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It can provide data confidentiality (to protect data from being observed by third parties) and/or data integrity protection (which protects the data from tampering).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] During TLS negotiation the server sends its X.509 certificate to prove its identity.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client may also send a certificate to prove its identity.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] After doing so, the client may then use SASL/EXTERNAL.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] By using the SASL/EXTERNAL, the client requests the server derive its identity from credentials provided at a lower level (such as TLS).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Though technically the server may use any identity information established at any lower level, typically the server will use the identity information established by TLS.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers also often support the non-standard "LDAPS" ("Secure LDAP", commonly known as "LDAP over SSL") protocol on a separate port, by default 636.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPS differs from LDAP in two ways: 1) upon connect, the client and server establish TLS before any LDAP messages are transferred (without a StartTLS operation) and 2) the LDAPS connection must be closed upon TLS closure.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some "LDAPS" client libraries only encrypt communication; they do not check the host name against the name in the supplied certificate.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Abandon operation requests that the server abort an operation named by a message ID.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Neither Abandon nor a successfully abandoned operation send a response.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A similar Cancel extended operation does send responses, but not all implementations support this.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Unbind operation abandons any outstanding operations and closes the connection.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name is of historical origin, and is *not* the opposite of the Bind operation.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients can abort a session by simply closing the connection, but they should use Unbind.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Unbind allows the server to gracefully close the connection and free resources that it would otherwise keep for some time until discovering the client had abandoned the connection.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It also instructs the server to cancel operations that can be canceled, and to not send responses for operations that cannot be canceled.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Most of the components described below are optional.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As in other URLs, special characters must be percent-encoded.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is a similar non-standard `ldaps` URI scheme for LDAP over SSL.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This should not be confused with LDAP with TLS, which is achieved using the StartTLS operation using the standard `ldap` scheme.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The contents of the entries in a subtree are governed by a directory schema, a set of definitions and constraints concerning the structure of the directory information tree (DIT).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema of a Directory Server defines a set of rules that govern the kinds of information that the server can hold.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes are the elements responsible for storing information in a directory, and the schema defines the rules for which attributes may be used in an entry, the kinds of values that those attributes may have, and how clients may interact with those values.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients may learn about the schema elements that the server supports by retrieving an appropriate subschema subentry.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Each entry must have an objectClass attribute, containing named classes defined in the schema.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema definition of the classes of an entry defines what kind of object the entry may represent - e.g. a person, organization or domain.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The object class definitions also define the list of attributes that must contain values and the list of attributes which may contain values.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, an entry representing a person might belong to the classes "top" and "person".
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Membership in the "person" class would require the entry to contain the "sn" and "cn" attributes, and allow the entry also to contain "userPassword", "telephoneNumber", and other attributes.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Since entries may have multiple ObjectClasses values, each entry has a complex of optional and mandatory attribute sets formed from the union of the object classes it represents.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] ObjectClasses can be inherited, and a single entry can have multiple ObjectClasses values that define the available and required attributes of the entry itself.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A parallel to the schema of an objectClass is a class definition and an instance in Object-oriented programming, representing LDAP objectClass and LDAP entry, respectively.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory servers may publish the directory schema controlling an entry at a base DN given by the entry's subschemaSubentry operational attribute.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Server administrators can add additional schema entries in addition to the provided schema elements.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A schema for representing individual people within organizations is termed a white pages schema.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection is a computer security attack similar to SQL injection that can occur when an application implementing LDAP fails to properly sanitize user input.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As an example, consider an LDAP search query that allows the user to search people by their name, the `cn` attribute.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A malicious user might replace a valid name with the `*` character, which matches any object with the `cn` attribute.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the application is vulnerable to this attack, it may display attributes that the searching user is not authorized to see.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection vulnerabilities are mitigated by escaping variables.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Escaping is accomplished with two distinct encoding functions — one for Distinguished Names and one for search strings — because they each allow different special characters.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some web frameworks come with escaping built in.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Like other parts of TCP/IP, LDAP was originally created without encryption.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This makes it vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks, in which attackers intercept credentials during the bind process.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This attack can be mitigated by requiring LDAPS or StartTLS during every bind involving credentials.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Much of the server operation is left to the implementor or administrator to decide.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Accordingly, servers may be set up to support a wide variety of scenarios.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, data storage in the server is not specified - the server may use flat files, databases, or just be a gateway to some other server.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Access control is not standardized, though there are commonly used models.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Users' passwords may be stored in their entries or elsewhere.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may refuse to perform operations when it wishes, and impose various limits.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Examples: One can define new operations.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] *Controls* may modify requests and responses, e.g. to request sorted search results.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] New search scopes and Bind methods can be defined.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes can have *options* that may modify their semantics.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As LDAP has gained momentum, vendors have provided it as an access protocol to other services.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The implementation then recasts the data to mimic the LDAP/X.500 model, but how closely this model is followed varies.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, there is software to access SQL databases through LDAP, even though LDAP does not readily lend itself to this.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, data previously held in other types of data stores are sometimes moved to LDAP directories.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, Unix user and group information can be stored in LDAP and accessed via PAM and NSS modules.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is often used by other services for authentication and/or authorization (what actions a given already-authenticated user can do on what service).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, in Active Directory Kerberos is used in the authentication step, while LDAP is used in the authorization step.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of such data model is the GLUE Schema, which is used in a distributed information system based on LDAP that enable users, applications and services to discover which services exist in a Grid infrastructure and further information about their structure and state.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP server may return referrals to other servers for requests that it cannot fulfill itself.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This requires a naming structure for LDAP entries so one can find a server holding a given distinguished name (DN), a concept defined in the X.500 Directory and also used in LDAP.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Another way of locating LDAP servers for an organization is a DNS server record (SRV).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An organization with the domain example.org may use the top level LDAP DN `dc=example, dc=org` (where *dc* means domain component).
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the LDAP server is also named ldap.example.org, the organization's top level LDAP URL becomes `ldap://ldap.example.org/dc=example,dc=org`.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Primarily two common styles of naming are used in both X.500 [2008] and LDAPv3.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These are documented in the ITU specifications and IETF RFCs.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The original form takes the top level object as the country object, such as `c=US`, `c=FR`.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The domain component model uses the model described above.
[src:ldap-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of country based naming could be `l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, c=FR`, or in the US: `cn=Common Name, l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, st=CA, c=US`.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] LDAP is a platform-independent protocol.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Several common Linux distributions include OpenLDAP Software for LDAP support.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The software also runs on BSD-variants, as well as AIX, Android, HP-UX, macOS, OpenVMS, Solaris, Microsoft Windows (NT and derivatives, e.g.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The OpenLDAP project was started in 1998 by Kurt Zeilenga.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The project started by cloning the LDAP reference source from the University of Michigan where a long-running project had supported development and evolution of the LDAP protocol until that project's final release in 1996.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] As of May 2015, the OpenLDAP project has four core team members: Howard Chu (chief architect), Quanah Gibson-Mount, Hallvard Furuseth, and Kurt Zeilenga.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] There are numerous other important and active contributors including Ondrej Kuznik, Luke Howard, Ryan Tandy, and Gavin Henry.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Past core team members include Pierangelo Masarati.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Historically the OpenLDAP server (slapd, the Standalone LDAP Daemon) architecture was split between a frontend that handles network access and protocol processing, and a backend that deals strictly with data storage.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] This split design was a feature of the original University of Michigan code written in 1996 and carried on in all subsequent OpenLDAP releases.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The original code included one main database backend and two experimental/demo backends.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The architecture is modular and many different backends are now available for interfacing to other technologies, not just traditional databases.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Note: In older (1.x) releases, the terms "backend" and "database" were often used interchangeably.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] To be precise, a "backend" is a class of storage interface, and a "database" is an instance of a backend.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The slapd server can use arbitrarily many backends at once, and can have arbitrarily many instances of each backend (i.e., arbitrarily many databases) active at once.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Currently 17 different backends are provided in the OpenLDAP distribution, and various third parties are known to maintain other backends independently.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Some backends available in older OpenLDAP releases have been retired from use, most notably back-ldbm which was inherited from the original UMich code, and back-tcl which was similar to back-perl and back-shell.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In practice, backends like -perl and -sock allow interfacing to any arbitrary programming language, thus providing limitless capabilities for customization and expansion.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In effect the slapd server becomes an RPC engine with a compact, well-defined and ubiquitous API.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Ordinarily an LDAP request is received by the frontend, decoded, and then passed to a backend for processing.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] When the backend completes a request, it returns a result to the frontend, which then sends the result to the LDAP client.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] An overlay is a piece of code that can be inserted between the frontend and the backend.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] It is thus able to intercept requests and trigger other actions on them before the backend receives them, and it can also likewise act on the backend's results before they reach the frontend.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Overlays have complete access to the slapd internal APIs, and so can invoke anything the frontend or other backends could perform.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Multiple overlays can be used at once, forming a stack of modules between the frontend and the backend.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Overlays provide a simple means to augment the functionality of a database without requiring that an entirely new backend be written, and allow new functionalities to be added in compact, easily debuggable and maintainable modules.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Since the introduction of the overlay feature in OpenLDAP 2.2 many new overlays have been contributed from the OpenLDAP community.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Currently there are 25 overlays in the core OpenLDAP distribution, with another 24 overlays in the user-contributed code section, and more awaiting approval for inclusion.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Backends and overlays are the two most commonly used types of modules.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Backends were typically built into the slapd binary, but they may also be built as dynamically loaded modules, and overlays are usually built as dynamic modules.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In addition, slapd supports dynamic modules for implementing new LDAP syntaxes, matching rules, controls, and extended operations, as well as for implementing custom access control mechanisms and password hashing mechanisms.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] OpenLDAP also supports SLAPI, the plugin architecture used by Sun and Netscape/Fedora/Red Hat.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In current releases, the SLAPI framework is implemented inside a slapd overlay.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] While many plugins written for Sun/Netscape/Fedora/Red Hat are compatible with OpenLDAP, very few members of the OpenLDAP community use SLAPI.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] OpenLDAP supports replication using Content Synchronization as specified in RFC 4533.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] This spec is hereafter referred to as "syncrepl".
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In addition to the base specification, an enhancement known as delta-syncrepl is also supported.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Additional enhancements have been implemented to support multi-master replication.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The basic synchronization operation is described in RFC 4533.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The protocol is defined such that a persistent database of changes is not required.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Rather the set of changes is implied via change sequence number (CSN) information stored in each entry and optimized via an optional session log which is particularly useful to track recent deletes.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The model of operation is that a replication client (consumer) sends a "content synchronizing search" to a replication server (provider).
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The consumer can provide a cookie in this search (especially when it has been in sync with the provider previously).
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In the OpenLDAP implementation of the RFC 4533, this cookie includes the latest CSN that has been received from the provider (called the contextCSN).
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] If the cookie is absent or indicates that the consumer is totally out of sync, then the provider will, in the refresh stage, send an add for each entry it has.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In the ideal case, the refresh stage of the response contains only a delete phase with just a small set of adds (including those that represent the current result of modifies) and deletes that have occurred since the time the consumer last synchronized with the provider.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] However, due to limited session log state (also non-persistent) kept in the provider, a present phase may be required, particularly including the presentation of all unchanged entries as a means (inefficient) of implying what has been deleted in the provider since the consumer last synchronized.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The search can be done in either refresh or refreshAndPersist mode, which implies what stages occur.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] During the refresh stage, two phases may occur: present and delete, where present always occurs before delete.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The phases are delimited via a sync info response that specifies which phase is completed.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The refresh and persist stages are also delimited via such sync info response.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] An optional optimization to more compactly represent a group of entries that are to be presented or deleted is to use a sync info response containing a syncIdSet that identifies the list of entryUUID values of those entries.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The present phase is differentiated from the delete phase as follows.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Entries that present unchanged entries may only be returned in the present phase.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Entries that delete entries may only be provided in the delete phase.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] In either phase, add entries (including adds that represent all current attributes of modified entries) can be returned.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] At the end of a present phase, each entry that the consumer has that was not identified in an add entry or present response during the present phase is implicitly no longer in the provider and thus must be deleted at the consumer so as to synchronize the consumer with the provider.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] Once the persist stage begins, the provider sends search results that indicate only the add, modify and delete of entries (no present unchanged entry indications) for those entries changed since the refresh stage completed.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The persist stage continues indefinitely, meaning that search has no final "done" response.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] By contrast, in the refresh mode only a refresh stage occurs and such stage completes with a done response that also ends the present or delete phase (whichever phase was currently active).
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] This protocol keeps a persistent database of write accesses (changes) and can represent each modify precisely (meaning only the attributes that have changed).
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] It is still built on the standard syncrepl specification, which always sends changes as complete entries.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] But in delta-syncrepl, the transmitted entries are actually sent from a log database, where each change in the main database is recorded as a log entry.
[src:ldap-directory/openldap] The log entries are recorded using the LDAP Log Schema.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Because these protocols used the OSI networking stack, a number of alternatives to DAP were developed to allow Internet clients to access the X.500 Directory using the TCP/IP networking stack.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The most well-known alternative to DAP is Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP).
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] While DAP and the other X.500 protocols can now use the TCP/IP networking stack, LDAP remains a popular directory access protocol.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The X.500 protocols traditionally use the OSI networking stack.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] However, the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) uses TCP/IP for transport.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] In later versions of the ITU Recommendation X.519, the Internet Directly-Mapped (IDM) protocols were introduced to allow X.500 protocol data units (PDUs) to be transported over the TCP/IP stack.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] This transport involves ISO Transport over TCP as well as a simple record-based binary protocol to frame protocol datagrams.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The primary concept of X.500 is that there is a single Directory Information Tree (DIT), a hierarchical organization of entries which are distributed across one or more servers, called Directory System Agents (DSA).
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] An entry consists of a set of attributes, each attribute with one or more values.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Each entry has a unique Distinguished Name, formed by combining its Relative Distinguished Name (RDN), one or more attributes of the entry itself, and the RDNs of each of the superior entries up to the root of the DIT.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] As LDAP implements a very similar data model to that of X.500, there is further description of the data model in the article on LDAP.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] X.520 and X.521 together provide a definition of a set of attributes and object classes to be used for representing people and organizations as entries in the DIT.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] They are one of the most widely deployed white pages schema.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] X.509, the portion of the standard providing for an authentication framework, is now also widely used outside of the X.500 directory protocols.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] It specifies a standard format for public-key certificates.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] X.509 was designed to be the secure access method for updating X.500 before the World Wide Web, but then as web browsers became popular, there needed to be a simple method of encrypting connections on the transport layer to web servers.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Hence, trusted root certificates for supported certificate authorities were pre-loaded into certificate storage areas on the communicating devices (e.g. personal computer, proxy, or web server).
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Added security is envisaged by the scheduled 2011-2014 implementation of the US National Strategy for Trusted Identities in Cyberspace, a two- to three-year project protecting digital identities in cyberspace.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The WWW e-commerce implementation of X.509v3 bypassed, but did not replace, the original ISO standard authentication mechanism of binding distinguished names in the X.500 Directory.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] These packages of certificates can be added or removed by the end user in their software, but are reviewed by browser and operating system vendors (such as Microsoft and Mozilla) in terms of their continued trustworthiness.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Should a problem arise, such as what occurred with DigiNotar, browser vendors can issue an update to mark a certificate authority as untrusted, but this is a serious removal effectively of that CA from "internet trust".
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] X.500 offers a way to view which organization claims a specific root certificate, outside of that provided bundle.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] This can function as a "4 corner model of trust" adding another check to determine if a root certificate has been compromised.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] For example, a web site using SSL, typically the DNS site name "www.foobar.com" is verified in a browser by the software using libraries that would check to see if the certificate was signed by one of the trusted root certificates given to the user.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Therefore, creating trust for users that they had reached the correct web site via HTTPS.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] However, stronger checks are also possible, to indicate that more than the domain name was verified.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] To contrast this with X.500, the certificate is one attribute of many for an entry, in which the entry could contain anything allowable by the specific Directory schema.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Thus X.500 does store the digital certificate, but it is one of many attributes that could potentially verify the organization, such as physical address, a contact telephone number and an email contact.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] This is in contrast with the Directory model which associates the attribute "caCertificate" with a listed certificate authority.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Thus the browser can verify the SSL cert of the website by means of the loaded group of accepted certificates or the root certificates can be looked up in an X.500 or LDAP Directory (or via HTTP/S) and imported into the list of trusted certificate authorities.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The "bound" distinguished name is located in the subject fields of the certificate which matches the Directory entry.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] X.509v3 can contain other extensions depending on the community of interest other than international domain names.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] For broad Internet use, RFC-5280 PKIX describes a profile for fields that may be useful for applications such as encrypted email.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The certificate itself is public and, because of its signature, considered to be unforgeable and can therefore be distributed in any manner, but an associated binding to an identity occurs in the Directory.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Binding is what links the certificate to the identity who claims to be using that certificate.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] For example, the X.500 software that runs the Federal Bridge has cross certificates that enable trust between certificate authorities.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] If a X.509v3 certificate is bound to a valid organization's distinguished name within the Directory, then a simple check can be made in regards to the authenticity of the certificate by a comparison with what is presented to the browser with what is present in the Directory.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Some options do exist to check notaries to see if a certificate has only recently been seen, and therefore more likely to have been compromised.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] If the cert is likely to be trusted and is failing because the domain name is a slight mismatch, it will then initially fail in the browser, but then be subjected to the notary trust, which can then bypass the browser warning.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] A valid organizational entry, such as o=FoobarWidgets, will also have an associated alphanumeric OID, and it has been "identity proofed" by ANSI, providing another layer of assurance regarding binding the certificate to the identity.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Some deployments (for example, the US Direct Project, which created standards for PKI in the healthcare industry) specify DNS-based publication of recipient S/MIME certificates, with options for DNS-based or LDAP-based discovery.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Early profiles used the DNS CERT Resource Record (RFC 4398); newer specifications define DANE mechanisms, including TLSA for TLS and SMIMEA for S/MIME.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] In practice, many production healthcare exchanges rely on curated trust-anchor bundles and directory/HTTP services, with DNSSEC/DANE adoption varying by ecosystem.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] DNS is sometimes preferred for storing and distributing information as it is highly available, and this can be applied to certificates and identities.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The concept of DNS root name servers has been contentious within the Internet community, though the issue is largely resolved for DNS.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] By contrast, the X.500 namespace has traditionally been viewed as starting with a national naming authority, mirroring ISO/ITU approaches with national representation.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Different countries therefore create their own unique X.500 services.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Events in 2011 highlighted threats from unknown nation-state actors forging certificates.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Similar techniques were used by Stuxnet to allow malicious software to impersonate trusted code – in that event, using stolen rather than forged certificates.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The aim of certificate transparency is to provide an end user with a simple procedure to determine whether a certificate is valid; checking only against the default bundle may be insufficient, hence the desire for an additional check.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] Other proposals for certificate transparency have also been advanced.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] A different attack affected Comodo, resulting in forged certificates targeting high-profile communications websites and necessitating urgent updates to major browsers.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] In that case, the certificates were actually issued by a trusted CA, leaving end users with no warning if they visited a spoofed site – unlike the Syrian incident, where the certificate was crudely forged (substituting "Alto Palo" for "Palo Alto") and contained incorrect serial numbers.
[src:ldap-directory/x-500] The authors of RFC 2693 – "*SPKI Certificate Theory,*" note that "The original X.500 plan is unlikely ever to come to fruition.
